 LINUX COMMANDS:  

1 . mkdir [directory_name]       PURPOSE:  Create a new directory 
  
2.  touch [file_name]            PURPOSE:  Create a new file.

3.  cat [file_name]              PURPOSE:  Show the contents of a file.

4.  clear                        PURPOSE:  Clear the terminal screen.

5.  ls                           PURPOSE:   List files and directories in the current directory.
  
6.  ls -a                        PURPOSE:   List all files and directories  in the current directory (shows hidden files).
 
7.  ls -l                        PURPOSE:   List files and directories in long format.
  
8.  pwd                          PURPOSE:   Show the directory you are currently working in.  
 
9.  cd ~                         PURPOSE:  Change directory to $HOME Move up one directory level.
 
10.  cd ..                       PURPOSE:  Change to the previous directory.
 
11.  cd [directory_path]         PURPOSE:  Change location to a specified directory.

12.  mk dir -p filename          PURPOSE:  Create a file inside the file.
     
13.  vi [file_name]              PURPOSE:  Open or create a file using the Vi/Vim text editor.
     vim [file_name]  

14.    i ----  insert

         esc then shift + colon (:)

         if to save the data use letter w

         if to quit, after saving letter q

         if to save and quit
     
